        "$:/language/Help/server": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/server",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki",
            "text": "The server built in to TiddlyWiki5 is very simple. Although compatible with TiddlyWeb it doesn't support many of the features needed for robust Internet-facing usage.\n\nAt the root, it serves a rendering of a specified tiddler. Away from the root, it serves individual tiddlers encoded in JSON, and supports the basic HTTP operations for `GET`, `PUT` and `DELETE`.\n\n```\n--server <port> <roottiddler> <rendertype> <servetype> <username> <password> <host>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''port'' - port number to serve from (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''roottiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\") \n* ''rendertype'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''servetype'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''username'' - the default username for signing edits\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n\nIf the password parameter is specified then the browser will prompt the user for the username and password. Note that the password is transmitted in plain text so this implementation isn't suitable for general use.\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n\nTo run multiple TiddlyWiki servers at the same time you'll need to put each one on a different port.\n"
        },

-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%; /* 2 */\n}\n\n/**\n * Remove default margin.\n */\n\nbody {\n    margin: 0;\n}\n\n/* ==========================================================================\n   Links\n   ========================================================================== */\n\n/**\n * Address `outline` inconsistency between Chrome and other browsers.\n */\n\na:focus {\n    outline: thin classic






!!What is AltBrowser?

AltBrowser is a tool and an experiment around an IDE for Smalltalk. A tool because it is usable, in production, as an IDE for [[Pharo/Smalltalk|http://www.pharo-project.org/home]]: it's complete, working and effective. An experiment because I use it to introduce new things and try new interaction modes.

A few features: [[Scoping]], GitIntegration, TextNavigation, FinderUI, DragAndDrop, RefactoringUndo, SmartSuggestions, MessageList, PackageExtensions, [[Performance]].

!!How does it look?

{{Screenshot.png}}

!!What are the goals

* A browser whose code is simple enough to be mastered by a single person.
* A browser usable for day to day development.
* A browser usable for small screen sizes
* A browser able to replace disparate GUI tools (message list, finder)

!!Secondary goals

All have been attained.

* Refactoring integration
* Reasonably sized menus and shortcuts
* Abstraction of significant Packaging concepts
* Scoping as a default
* Entirely keyboard-driven
* Git integration
* No search bar :)
* Learn about RPackage and friends.

!!How to use

AltBrowser is hosted on [[github|https://github.com/ThierryGoubier/AltBrowser]].

!!Related

AltBrowser is not the first attempt: here is a list of RelatedProjects, with much to learn from them.







Drag and drop is a common feature in system browsers. Here, some additions are to support a higher-level view of Packages.

In short, I found painfull to write extension protocols, so drag and drop can be used for that: drop a method on a Package, and it will be moved into the extension protocol of that package.






Instead of having a specific window for the Finder, the Finder UI is integrated in the GUI.

{{FinderUI.png}}

Look how I managed to get rid of the Package selection part of the original Finder UI?

{{OldFinderUI.png}} It's not necessary anymore, since the underlying browser can be scoped.

Now, why would I need a specific GUI for displaying the results?

{{FinderUIResult.png}} No, I can use the same :)

AltBrowser contains a small attempt at git integration. It is simply a version viewer which is able to search through git (instead of the changes) for versions of a method, and is triggered if the method you are asking versions for is in a package with a gitfiletree repository.

The Newspeak browser is probably the newest browser available in the Smalltalk universe. It is interesting to read a paper on it and the underlying framework, Hopscotch.

* [[Hopscotch|http://bracha.org/hopscotch-wasdett.pdf]]

It is an interesting read, and explains well the motivation behind the Newspeak browser. Why not use something like that? Well, they focus on reproducing a web browser. I'm old enough to have started my academic career on the problem of navigation in hypertexts, and, as such, I've never found that the web browser represented a very good solution. This can be shown by two things in navigating the web: navigation bars on the side of web pages, even to be able to read a single page. And google. Both those are trying to compensate for the 'lost in hyperspace' effect of old.

So, when browsing code, I need a map of where I am. The tree is that map. Newspeak does not offer that, even if the single page view is interesting (and maybe I'll consider it).

Package extensions in Monticello are something complex. You have to remember that the protocol is *name-of-the-package, create that protocol and add your method in it.

So, in AltBrowser, extensions are mapped directly to an *extensions node in the package, and the protocol is never shown, since it's redundant information.

{{PackageExtensions.png}}

Look at the same in PackageTreeNautilus, and note how much information is redundant:

{{PackageExtensionsNautilus.png}} I'm looking at an extension, I don't need to be recalled that the name of the extension is the same as the package I selected two panes to the left.

Note that, when doing the operation with Nautilus, I had two issues:

* First, the package extensions are listed among all the classes of that package (even if those classes are classified in tags: AltBrowser filter that out, see above).

* And then, in the protocol pane, I had to find and select the extension protocol itself. In a class with many packages, I'll have to scroll down (or use a text search on the protocol name).

The greyed out items in Nautilus are a nice touch.

What's missing in AltBrowser is the mapping from the class view.

AltBrowser is fast: fast to open.

Because the GUI is simple and that the tree widget shows few elements.

Data points:

| Expression | Time |
| Time millisecondsToRun: [ 10 timesRepeat: [ AltBrowser open ] ]. | 927 |
| Time millisecondsToRun: [ 10 timesRepeat: [ PackageTreeNautilus open ] ]. | 6590 |
| Time millisecondsToRun: [ 10 timesRepeat: [ Browser open ] ]. | 2853 |

There is little difference between PackageTreeNautilus and Nautilus. AltBrowser has no performance tuning, no icon cache, nothing of the sort.






Many interesting projects have already been tried along those ways; it shows in the sense that Morphic has fairly good support for trees. Thanks to the pharo-dev contributors for that list!

* The standard Smalltalk System Browser : simple at start, grew more complex as smalltalk images grew larger. A very early example at : [[http://www.chilton-computing.org.uk/inf/pngs/wm_fig4p1.png]]
* The Omni Browser : http://scg.unibe.ch/archive/papers/Berg07cOmnibrowser.pdf
* The Nautilus Browser : http://marianopeck.wordpress.com/2012/02/26/nautilus-the-reborn-of-the-systembrowser/
* The [[Whisker Browser]] : http://www.fit.vutbr.cz/study/courses/OMP/public/software/sqcdrom2/Packages/Tools/Whisker/
* The Newspeak browser : http://newspeaklanguage.org/
* The StarBrowser : http://wiki.squeak.org/squeak/2935
* The Creativity Browser: https://github.com/sebastianconcept/Creativity

At first glance, the AltBrowser looks very simple compared to those efforts. Internally, it is in part inspired by the command structure of the Omni Browser. Externally, it tries to adhere to simple HCI guidelines.

It provides for [[user-driven, user-organized|UserOrganized]] packages and class as a primary object of focus. In its GUI, it's less radical than both Whisker and the [[Newspeak]] browser. The software architecture of the AltBrowser is fairly similar to the Star Browser (menu), but not as radical (less ambitious?) and a lot simpler.






AltBrowser is scoped. What does this means? That every browser is relative to a Refactoring environment (RBEnvironment), and displays (TreeFiltering) and behaves (ScopedQueries) according to what is visible into that environment.

This also means that creating a scope is a natural operation:

* Double click on a package → new browser scoped on that package.
* Double click on a class → new browse scoped on that class
* Senders / Finder / implementors → new browser scoped on the result of the search

Scoping is hierarchical:

* Senders in a class scope → result scoped inside the class scope

Now, my task is to find a way to:

* Toggle between scoped and global queries

!with the AltBrowser.

Does AltBrowser makes it simpler to get to Smalltalk/Pharo? This tutorial will explore that idea, and be some material for teaching for me.

# Starting with a bare Pharo 3.0 image, install the stable version of AltBrowser from the configuration browser.
# Open the Monticello browser, create a new package to hold the code you will create. Try to avoid using a name beginning with the same name as an existing package.
# Open a system browser. You will normally see your package on the left pane.







The StarBrowser is interesting and looks similar to the AltBrowser, but I wouldn't classify it as a browser. It is a classifying GUI combined with a browser.

The problem with the StarBrowser is that classifying is hard, especially if you have to do it from scratch. And that it doesn't manage to avoid having the full system browser on the side. Simpler ways of classifying, such as easily restricting the view in the browser, could well be a satisfying answer and is provided by [[Scoping]].

Side note: the AltBrowser could be used to show an arbitrary collection of code objects, without any changes in its code. Hence, using it to reproduce the StarBrowser would be very easy.






This example shows the text navigation features, as a sequence of images.

As an example, we will navigate to the ~ConfigurationOfOSProcess, which is classified under Configuration inside Packages.

First, when an AltBrowser opens on a Pharo3 image, it looks like that:

{{TextNavigation00.png}}

Then we press 'P', 'a', 'c': 

{{TextNavigation02.png}} A small text area appears, and the tree starts selecting the item 'Packages'.

Then we press 'Enter':

{{TextNavigation03.png}} The 'Packages' category opens.

Then we press 'C' 'o' 'n' 'f':

{{TextNavigation04.png}} After selecting 'CI', 'Configuration' is selected.

Then we press 'Tab', 'O', 'f', 'O', 'S':

{{TextNavigation05.png}} 'Configuration' opens, and 'OfOSProcess' is selected.

Then we press 'Tab':

The TextNavigation is very simple, due to the extensibility of Morphic.

On each key press in the tree (which is not handled by commands), add a text editing morph above the tree and give it the focus.

On each key press in the text morph, select the right item in the tree (whose name begins with the contents of the text morph).

On 'Enter' and 'Tab', expand the selected item and delete the text morph.

On anything else, delete the text morph.

A bit of tuning to make sure it works nicely. No knowledge of the underlying model is necessary.






The AltBrowser has a tree widget, on the left, which is a filtered representation of the tree of code.

Nodes appear or not depending on: do they belong to the environment (see [[Scoping]]) and are they empty (no childitems) or not.

Nodes names depend too of what is visible. For example, if a Package node is Monticello, then a subnode named Monticello-Core is given the opportunity to reduce itself to Core. This makes the tree a lot more compact. It is visible in [[Screenshot.png]] where the Core node under Alt-Browser refers in fact to the system category Alt-Browser-Core.






The AltBrowser started with a significant feature: let the user organize himself the tree of packages, the class ordering inside a package, the protocol ordering in a class.

With developments in Pharo, this feature has been progressively removed. Why? Because many elements of the underlying structure are not ordering-compliant: Monticello, ProtocolOrganizer.

So, instead, AltBrowser moved to providing a reasonable default ordering, similar to what was done in the past by hand.

For protocols, in the following order:

* extensions
* initialization protocols
* alphabetical ordering of remaining protocols
* private protocols

For packages:

* Categories first
* Packages

The purpose is to set an order that we can rely on to remember where things are.






The Whisker Browser share some features with AltBrowser such as the context-sensitive popup menus on a heterogeneous collection of items.

AltBrowser goes a lot further than that, since shortcuts are also context-sensitive and automatically in sync with the popup menus. And popup menus taps into SmartSuggestions as well.

For the main feature, I'd classify the Whisker Browser along the same lines as a Tiling Window Manager, for layout space organisation. The Whisker browser too tries to compensate the waste of space in the original system browser.
